<i>with Gladstone.</i>

322
00:15:08,600 --> 00:15:12,280
<i>This unique film</i>
<i>provides a rare glimpse</i>

323
00:15:12,320 --> 00:15:16,840
<i>into the private world</i>
<i>of a woman who ruled</i>
<i>half the earth.</i>

324
00:15:16,880 --> 00:15:20,600
<i>The commentary, recorded on</i>
<i>the earliest wax cylinders,</i>

325
00:15:20,640 --> 00:15:24,880
<i>is spoken by</i>
<i>Alfred Lord Tennyson,</i>
<i>the poet laureate.</i>

326
00:15:24,920 --> 00:15:27,400
TENNYSON:
<i>Well, hello,</i>
<i>it's the wacky queen again.</i>

327
00:15:27,440 --> 00:15:30,480
<i>And who's the other fella?</i>
<i>It's Willie Gladstone.</i>

328
00:15:30,520 --> 00:15:33,480
<i>And when these two way-out,</i>
<i>wacky characters get together,</i>

329
00:15:33,520 --> 00:15:35,320
<i>there's fun aplenty.</i>

330
00:15:35,360 --> 00:15:38,040
<i>And, uh-oh,</i>
<i>there's a hosepipe.</i>

331
00:15:38,080 --> 00:15:40,040
<i>This means trouble</i>
<i>for somebody.</i>

332
00:15:40,080 --> 00:15:42,640
<i>Uh-oh. Charlie Gardener's</i>
<i>fallen for that old trick.</i>

333
00:15:42,680 --> 00:15:45,080
<i>Queenie's put him</i>
<i>in a heap of trouble.</i>

334
00:15:45,120 --> 00:15:47,360
<i>Uh-oh! That's one</i>
<i>in the eye for Willie.</i>

335
00:15:47,400 --> 00:15:49,320
<i>Here, you have a look.</i>

336
00:15:49,360 --> 00:15:52,360
[♪]

337
00:15:57,920 --> 00:16:00,320
<i>Well, doggone it,</i>
<i>where's that water?</i>

338
00:16:02,240 --> 00:16:05,360
<i>Uh-oh! There it is,</i>
<i>all over his face.</i>

339
00:16:13,680 --> 00:16:16,720
<i>Well, hello.</i>
<i>What's Britain's</i>
<i>wacky queen up to now?</i>

340
00:16:16,760 --> 00:16:19,160
<i>Well, she's certainly not</i>
<i>sitting on the fence.</i>

341
00:16:19,200 --> 00:16:21,080
<i>She's painting it.</i>

342
00:16:21,120 --> 00:16:23,320
<i>Surely, nothing</i>
<i>can go wrong here.</i>

343
00:16:23,360 --> 00:16:26,840
<i>Uh-oh. Here's the PM</i>
<i>coming back for more.</i>

344
00:16:26,880 --> 00:16:28,760
<i>And he certainly gets it.</i>

345
00:16:44,040 --> 00:16:46,840
<i>Well, that's one way to get</i>
<i>the housework done.</i>

346
00:16:46,880 --> 00:16:48,040
[♪]

347
00:17:04,320 --> 00:17:05,800
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

348
00:17:14,240 --> 00:17:17,120
Oh, Dad, look who's
come to see us.

349
00:17:17,160 --> 00:17:18,440
It's our Ken.

350
00:17:18,480 --> 00:17:19,680
[SPITS]

351
00:17:19,720 --> 00:17:22,560
Aye, and about bloody time
if you ask me.

352
00:17:22,600 --> 00:17:24,200
Aren't you pleased
to see me, Father?

353
00:17:24,240 --> 00:17:26,440
Yes, of course he's
pleased to see you, Ken.

354
00:17:26,480 --> 00:17:29,160
All right, woman. All right.
I've got a tongue in me head.

355
00:17:29,200 --> 00:17:30,440
I'll do the talking.

356
00:17:31,840 --> 00:17:33,240
Blimey.

357
00:17:33,280 --> 00:17:35,240
I like your fancy suit.

358
00:17:35,280 --> 00:17:37,520
Is that what they're wearing
up in Yorkshire now?

359
00:17:37,560 --> 00:17:39,720
-It's just an ordinary suit,
Father.
-Ah.

360
00:17:39,760 --> 00:17:41,280
It's all I've got
apart from the overalls.

361
00:17:42,840 --> 00:17:44,680
How are you liking it
down the mine, Ken?

362
00:17:44,720 --> 00:17:46,440
Oh, it's not
too bad, Mum.

363
00:17:46,480 --> 00:17:48,240
We're using some new
tungsten carbide drills

364
00:17:48,280 --> 00:17:50,560
for the preliminary coal-face
scouring operations.

365
00:17:50,600 --> 00:17:52,200
Ooh, that sounds
nice, dear.

366
00:17:52,240 --> 00:17:55,360
Tungsten carbide drills?

367
00:17:55,400 --> 00:17:58,440
What in the bloody hell
is tungsten carbide drills?

368
00:17:58,480 --> 00:18:00,920
It's something they use
in coal mining, Father.

369
00:18:00,960 --> 00:18:03,160
"It's something they use
in coal mining, Father."

370
00:18:03,200 --> 00:18:05,440
You're bloody fancy talk
since you left London.

371
00:18:05,480 --> 00:18:06,960
Not that again.

372
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:08,480
Oh. He-- He's had
a hard day, dear.

373
00:18:08,520 --> 00:18:11,360
His new play opens at
National Theatre tomorrow.

374
00:18:11,400 --> 00:18:13,040
Oh. That's good.

375
00:18:13,080 --> 00:18:15,600
Good? Good?
What do you know about it?

376
00:18:15,640 --> 00:18:18,920
What do you know about
getting up at 5:00 in
the morning to fly to Paris,

377
00:18:18,960 --> 00:18:20,680
back at the Old Vic
for drinks at 12,

378
00:18:20,720 --> 00:18:23,440
sweating the day through
press interviews,
television interviews,

379
00:18:23,480 --> 00:18:25,720
then getting back here at 10
to wrestle with the problem

380
00:18:25,760 --> 00:18:27,760
of a homosexual nymphomaniac
drug addict

381
00:18:27,800 --> 00:18:30,520
involved in the ritual murder
of a well-known Scottish
footballer?

382
00:18:30,560 --> 00:18:32,880
That's a full working day, lad.

383
00:18:32,920 --> 00:18:34,560
And don't you forget it!

384
00:18:34,600 --> 00:18:36,600
-Oh, don't shout
at the boy, Father.
-Aye.

385
00:18:36,640 --> 00:18:39,680
Hampstead wasn't
good enough for you, was it?

386
00:18:39,720 --> 00:18:42,040
You had to go
poncing off to Barnsley.

387
00:18:43,880 --> 00:18:46,120
You and your coal-mining
friends.

388
00:18:46,160 --> 00:18:48,560
-[SPITS]
-Coal mining is
a wonderful thing, Father.

389
00:18:48,600 --> 00:18:51,000
-Yeah.
-But it's something
you'll never understand.

390
00:18:51,040 --> 00:18:53,520
-Just look at you!
-Oh, Ken, be careful.

391
00:18:53,560 --> 00:18:55,600
You know what he's like
after a few novels.

392
00:18:55,640 --> 00:18:57,720
What? What?
What?

393
00:18:57,760 --> 00:18:59,280
Come on, lad.
Come on.

394
00:18:59,320 --> 00:19:01,640
Out with it.
What's wrong with me?

395
00:19:01,680 --> 00:19:03,760
You tit!

396
00:19:03,800 --> 00:19:05,200
I'll tell you what's
wrong with you.

397
00:19:05,240 --> 00:19:07,240
Your head's addled
with novels and poems.

398
00:19:07,280 --> 00:19:09,840
You come home every evening
reeling of Château Latour.

399
00:19:09,880 --> 00:19:12,000
-Don't, don't.
-Look what you've done
to Mother.

400
00:19:12,040 --> 00:19:13,560
She's worn out with
meeting film stars,

401
00:19:13,600 --> 00:19:16,360
attending premieres
and giving gala luncheons.

402
00:19:16,400 --> 00:19:19,880
There's nowt wrong
with gala luncheons, lad!

403
00:19:19,920 --> 00:19:22,760
I've had more gala luncheons
than you've had hot dinners.

404
00:19:22,800 --> 00:19:25,560
-[CRYING] Oh, please, please.
-Ahh! Aahh!

405
00:19:25,600 --> 00:19:27,320
-Oh! Oh, no!
-What is it?

406
00:19:27,360 --> 00:19:29,880
Oh, it's his writer's cramp.

407
00:19:29,920 --> 00:19:31,480
You never told me
about this.

408
00:19:31,520 --> 00:19:33,360
No, we didn't
like to, Kenny.

409
00:19:33,400 --> 00:19:36,040
I'm all right.
I'm all right, woman.
Just get him out of here.

410
00:19:36,080 --> 00:19:37,760
Oh, Ken.
You'd better go.

411
00:19:37,800 --> 00:19:39,400
All right.
I'm going.

412
00:19:39,440 --> 00:19:41,280
After all we've
done for him.

413
00:19:41,320 --> 00:19:43,560
One day you'll realize there's
more to life than culture.

414
00:19:43,600 --> 00:19:45,120
There's dirt and smoke,

415
00:19:45,160 --> 00:19:46,440
-and good honest sweat!
-Get out!

416
00:19:46,480 --> 00:19:48,720
Get out, you laborer!

417
00:19:51,360 --> 00:19:55,000
Hey. You know, Mother,
I think there's a play there.
Get agent on the phone.

418
00:19:55,040 --> 00:19:57,320
Aye, I think
you're right, Frank.

419
00:19:57,360 --> 00:19:59,000
-It could express--
-[KNOCKING ON FLOOR]

420
00:19:59,040 --> 00:20:02,120
-It could express
a vital theme of our age.
-Ah.

421
00:20:02,160 --> 00:20:05,480
Oh, shut up!
Shut up!

422
00:20:06,840 --> 00:20:08,200
Well, that's better.

423
00:20:08,240 --> 00:20:09,960
Now, for something
completely different.

424
00:20:10,000 --> 00:20:11,400
A man with three buttocks.

425
00:20:11,440 --> 00:20:12,720
DAD AND MOM:
We've done that!

426
00:20:12,760 --> 00:20:14,640
Oh, all right! All right!

427
00:20:16,560 --> 00:20:20,240
A man with... nine legs.

428
00:20:20,280 --> 00:20:22,080
-MAN: He ran away.
-Oh, bloody hell.

429
00:20:24,280 --> 00:20:25,400
Uh...

430
00:20:27,240 --> 00:20:29,080
A-- A Scotsman
on a horse.

